    <!-- Section 1: Lake Ontario Impact -->
    <section id="lake-ontario-impact" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6 pb-3 border-b-2 border-cyan-600">
        1. Lake Ontario's Hidden Impact on Oakville Basements
      </h2>

      <div class="prose prose-slate max-w-none">
        <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Lake Ontario sits less than 2 kilometers from Oakville's southern boundary, creating a persistent high water table that affects basement waterproofing across the entire town. The lake's average elevation of 75 meters above sea level establishes a baseline groundwater pressure that pushes moisture inland, particularly during spring melt and heavy rainfall events when lake levels rise.
        </p>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Properties south of the Queen Elizabeth Way experience the most direct lake influence. Neighborhoods like Old Oakville, Bronte Village, and Morrison experience water table depths of just 1.5-3 meters below grade during wet seasons. This shallow water table creates constant hydrostatic pressure against foundation walls, making exterior waterproofing with proper drainage systems essential rather than optional.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-cyan-50 border-l-4 border-cyan-600 p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-cyan-900 mb-3">Lake Effect on Oakville Water Tables</h3>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-700">
            <li><strong>South of QEW:</strong> Water table 1.5-3m deep, constant hydrostatic pressure</li>
            <li><strong>Between QEW and Dundas:</strong> Water table 3-5m deep, seasonal fluctuation</li>
            <li><strong>North of Dundas Street:</strong> Water table 5-8m deep, minimal lake influence</li>
            <li><strong>Spring lake levels (April-May):</strong> +30cm above winter average</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The prevailing southwest winds off Lake Ontario deliver 20-30% more precipitation to Oakville's lakefront neighborhoods compared to inland areas north of Upper Middle Road. This precipitation pattern, combined with clay-heavy glacial till soils that drain slowly, creates perfect conditions for basement moisture problems. Homes along Lakeshore Road East and West between Trafalgar Road and Dorval Drive face the highest risk.
        </p>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Lake Ontario's thermal influence extends inland for several kilometers, creating freeze-thaw cycles that differ from Toronto's patterns. Oakville experiences approximately 40-50 freeze-thaw events per winter, with lakefront areas seeing 15-20% fewer hard freezes than properties north of Highway 403. This moderated climate allows contractors to perform waterproofing work later into fall and earlier in spring, but it also means foundation movement from frost heave continues through mild winter periods.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Lakefront Estate Waterproofing Considerations</h3>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Premium lakefront properties between Colonel William Parkway and Bronte Road require specialized waterproofing approaches due to their proximity to the lake. These estates, many valued above $3 million, typically feature walkout basements, multi-level foundation designs, and extensive below-grade living spaces that demand comprehensive moisture protection.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-slate-100 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4">Lakefront Waterproofing Requirements</h4>
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
            <div>
              <p class="font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">Foundation Depth</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-slate-700">Excavate 8-12 feet to reach footings below water table</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <p class="font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">Drainage System</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-slate-700">Heavy-duty weeping tile system with redundant sump capacity</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <p class="font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">Membrane</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-slate-700">Rubberized asphalt or bentonite for high hydrostatic pressure</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <p class="font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">Conservation Permit</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-slate-700">Required for work within 15m of Lake Ontario shoreline</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Properties with direct lake access or those within Conservation Halton's Lake Ontario Shoreline regulatory area face additional permitting requirements. Any excavation within 15 meters of the lake's high-water mark requires Conservation Halton approval, adding 21-45 days to project timelines. These properties often need geotechnical assessments to ensure waterproofing excavation won't destabilize shoreline slopes or impact natural heritage features.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 2: Creek Flooding -->
    <section id="creek-flooding" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6 pb-3 border-b-2 border-cyan-600">
        2. Sixteen Mile Creek & Morrison Creek: Oakville's Flood Corridors
      </h2>

      <div class="prose prose-slate max-w-none">
        <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Sixteen Mile Creek carves a north-south corridor through Oakville's core, draining 369 square kilometers of watershed before emptying into Lake Ontario at Oakville Harbour. The creek's floodplain extends 50-200 meters on either side of the main channel, affecting hundreds of properties in Old Oakville, Bronte, and areas along Sixteen Mile Drive and Morrison Road.
        </p>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Homes within the creek's regulatory floodplain face elevated basement flooding risk during spring melt and heavy rainfall events. The watershed's urbanized upper reaches deliver rapid runoff, creating flash flood conditions that can raise creek levels by 2-3 meters within hours. Properties along Chartwell Road, Pine Glen Road, and streets adjacent to Glen Abbey Golf Course experience the highest frequency of flood-related basement moisture intrusion.
        </p>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto my-8">
          <table class="min-w-full bg-white border border-slate-300 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
            <thead class="bg-slate-800 text-white">
              <tr>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left text-sm font-semibold">Creek System</th>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left text-sm font-semibold">Affected Neighborhoods</th>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left text-sm font-semibold">Flood Risk Level</th>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left text-sm font-semibold">Permit Requirements</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-slate-200">
              <tr>
