              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-slate-900 font-medium">Fourteen Mile Creek</td>
                <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-slate-700">West Oak Trails, Clearview</td>
                <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-slate-700">Moderate</td>
                <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-slate-700">Conservation Halton</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="bg-slate-50">
                <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-slate-900 font-medium">McCraney Creek</td>
                <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-slate-700">Southeast Oakville</td>
                <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-slate-700">Low-Moderate</td>
                <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-slate-700">Town Building Permit</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Sixteen Mile Creek Floodplain Properties</h3>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Properties within the Sixteen Mile Creek's regulatory floodplain must implement comprehensive flood protection measures during basement waterproofing projects. This includes backwater valves on all below-grade drainage connections, oversized sump pump systems with battery backup, and elevated mechanical equipment to prevent flood damage.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-600 p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-amber-900 mb-3">Floodplain Waterproofing Checklist</h3>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-700">
            <li>✓ <strong>Backwater valve:</strong> CSA-approved installation on foundation drain and sanitary connections</li>
            <li>✓ <strong>Dual sump system:</strong> Primary pump + backup with 12-hour battery capacity</li>
            <li>✓ <strong>High-water alarm:</strong> Audible and remote monitoring notification</li>
            <li>✓ <strong>Elevated utilities:</strong> Furnace, water heater, electrical panel above flood level</li>
            <li>✓ <strong>Flood-resistant materials:</strong> Concrete or tile below flood elevation, no drywall</li>
            <li>✓ <strong>Foundation drainage:</strong> 6-inch weeping tile minimum, gravel surround</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Morrison Creek, which flows through the eastern portion of Oakville before joining Sixteen Mile Creek, creates similar challenges for properties along Postmaster Drive, William Halton Parkway, and neighborhoods east of Third Line. The creek's relatively steep gradient causes rapid water level fluctuations during storms, with peak flows occurring 2-4 hours after heavy rainfall begins.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Conservation Halton Regulated Areas</h3>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Conservation Halton regulates development and construction activities within creek valleys, floodplains, and areas with steep slopes throughout Oakville. Basement waterproofing projects that involve excavation within these regulated areas require permits to ensure work doesn't increase flooding risk, destabilize slopes, or impact aquatic habitats.
        </p>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The permit application process requires site plans showing excavation limits, drainage details, and erosion control measures. Conservation Halton typically reviews applications within 21 business days for straightforward projects, but complex sites near creek channels or on steep slopes may require geotechnical reports and extended review periods of 45-60 days. Budget an additional $650-$1,200 for permit fees and engineering assessments when waterproofing within regulated areas.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-slate-100 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4">Properties Requiring Conservation Halton Permits</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-3 text-slate-700">
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-cyan-600 font-bold mr-3">•</span>
              <span>Within 15 meters of Lake Ontario shoreline</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-cyan-600 font-bold mr-3">•</span>
              <span>Within defined floodplain of Sixteen Mile Creek or Morrison Creek</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-cyan-600 font-bold mr-3">•</span>
              <span>On slopes greater than 15% grade</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-cyan-600 font-bold mr-3">•</span>
              <span>Within 30 meters of top-of-bank of any watercourse</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-cyan-600 font-bold mr-3">•</span>
              <span>In designated valley or stream corridor areas</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
