    <!-- Section 3: Heritage Foundations -->
    <section id="heritage-foundations" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6 pb-3 border-b-2 border-cyan-600">
        3. Heritage Stone Foundations in Old Oakville
      </h2>

      <div class="prose prose-slate max-w-none">
        <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Old Oakville's heritage homes, concentrated between Navy Street, Allan Street, Lakeshore Road, and Trafalgar Road, represent some of the GTA's finest examples of early 20th century residential architecture. Many of these properties, built between 1900 and 1950, feature original stone foundations constructed from locally quarried limestone or fieldstone gathered from area farms.
        </p>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          These stone foundations present unique waterproofing challenges compared to modern poured concrete. The mortar joints between stones deteriorate over 70-100 years of freeze-thaw cycles, creating pathways for moisture infiltration. Stone foundations typically lack the reinforcement and consistent thickness of concrete, making them more susceptible to lateral soil pressure and settlement cracks.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-purple-50 border-l-4 border-purple-600 p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-purple-900 mb-3">Heritage Foundation Assessment Checklist</h3>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-700">
            <li><strong>Mortar condition:</strong> Check for crumbling, missing joints, or previous repointing</li>
            <li><strong>Stone integrity:</strong> Look for spalling, cracks, or loose stones</li>
            <li><strong>Foundation thickness:</strong> Measure wall thickness (typically 16-24 inches)</li>
            <li><strong>Structural movement:</strong> Document cracks, bulges, or leaning sections</li>
            <li><strong>Interior finish:</strong> Assess lime plaster or parge coat condition</li>
            <li><strong>Heritage designation:</strong> Verify if property is individually designated or in heritage district</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Waterproofing Approaches for Stone Foundations</h3>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Stone foundations in heritage homes typically require a hybrid waterproofing approach that combines exterior drainage improvements with interior moisture management. Full exterior excavation and membrane application, while ideal, may not be feasible if the foundation shows structural instability or if heritage designation restricts exterior alterations.
        </p>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
          <div class="bg-white border-2 border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-6">
            <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-3 flex items-center">
              <span class="bg-green-600 text-white rounded-full w-8 h-8 flex items-center justify-center mr-3 text-sm">1</span>
              Exterior Approach
            </h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-700 mb-3">Best for structurally sound foundations</p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
              <li>• Excavate full foundation depth</li>
              <li>• Repoint mortar joints as needed</li>
              <li>• Apply breathable membrane system</li>
              <li>• Install drainage board and weeping tile</li>
              <li>• Backfill with free-draining gravel</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-slate-900 mt-4">Cost: $195-$280/linear foot</p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-white border-2 border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-6">
            <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-3 flex items-center">
              <span class="bg-cyan-600 text-white rounded-full w-8 h-8 flex items-center justify-center mr-3 text-sm">2</span>
              Interior Approach
            </h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-700 mb-3">For unstable or designated foundations</p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
              <li>• Install interior perimeter drain</li>
              <li>• Add sump pump system with backup</li>
              <li>• Apply crystalline waterproofing</li>
              <li>• Install vapor barrier and drainage mat</li>
              <li>• Finish with studded moisture-resistant wall</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-slate-900 mt-4">Cost: $125-$185/linear foot</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Many heritage homes in Old Oakville have undergone partial foundation updates over the decades. It's common to find a mix of original stone sections, concrete block additions from mid-century renovations, and modern poured concrete where additions were built. Each section requires appropriate waterproofing treatment based on its construction method and condition.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Heritage Designation Implications</h3>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The Town of Oakville maintains a Heritage Register with over 200 designated properties, concentrated heavily in Old Oakville's Heritage Conservation District. Individually designated properties require Heritage Permit approval for any exterior alterations visible from the street, which may include foundation excavation work on corner lots or properties with exposed foundation walls.
        </p>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Within the Heritage Conservation District, bounded roughly by Lakeshore Road, Navy Street, Kerr Street, and Trafalgar Road, all exterior work requires review by the Town's Heritage Conservation Committee. For waterproofing projects, this typically focuses on ensuring excavation is properly restored, that foundation parging matches historic appearance, and that new window wells or drainage features don't compromise the property's heritage character.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-slate-100 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4">Heritage Permit Process for Waterproofing</h4>
          <ol class="space-y-3 text-slate-700">
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="font-bold text-purple-600 mr-3">1.</span>
              <div>
                <p class="font-semibold">Submit Heritage Permit Application</p>
                <p class="text-sm">Include site plan, foundation photos, scope of work description</p>
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
