        <div class="bg-emerald-50 border-l-4 border-emerald-600 p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-emerald-900 mb-3">Insurance Considerations for Finished Basements</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-3">Many Oakville homeowners discover too late that standard home insurance policies exclude or severely limit basement flooding coverage, particularly for finished spaces. Here's what affects coverage:</p>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-700">
            <li><strong>Sewer backup endorsement:</strong> Separate rider required, typically $200-400/year premium</li>
            <li><strong>Overland water coverage:</strong> Relatively new offering, covers surface water intrusion</li>
            <li><strong>Waterproofing documentation:</strong> Photos and receipts proving proper installation may be required for claims</li>
            <li><strong>Maintenance records:</strong> Annual sump pump testing and drain cleaning logs support claims</li>
            <li><strong>Deductibles:</strong> Water damage deductibles often $5,000-$10,000, separate from main policy</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Consult with insurance brokers before finishing basement spaces to understand coverage limitations and requirements. Some insurers mandate specific waterproofing features (backwater valve, sump pump backup, alarm system) before providing coverage for high-value basement improvements. Documentation of proper waterproofing installation, including photos and contractor certifications, should be added to home insurance files before beginning finish work.
        </p>
